{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":4012,"record_hash":"sha256:bcd8fcf096f2159268ab703440c782a9d4db74c7e211d5a4d595e86b2ee7f0b4","timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:31:17.813Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I dug deeper. My updated read: `hazler-secrets` is still the best POC-sized embed, and `keyhog` is the more serious “maybe later” engine.\n\n| Option | Fit | Notes |\n|---|---:|---|\n| [`hazler-secrets`](https://docs.rs/hazler-secrets/latest/hazler_secrets/) | Best POC fit | Small MIT Rust library. Has `SecretScanner::scan_with_entropy(...)`, pattern findings, and high-entropy findings. Findings include line/column/context, though matched text may already be redacted, so I’d use it to decide “mask this JSON string value,” not to surgically replace substrings. |\n| [`keyhog-scanner` + `keyhog-core`](https://docs.rs/keyhog-scanner/latest/keyhog_scanner/) | Strong but heavier | Real engine shape: detector specs, raw matches, offsets, confidence, entropy, decode-through scanning. `keyhog-core` also has embedded detectors and redacted output types. But it brings a much larger dependency/features surface, including [REDACTED:entropy] defaults. Feels post-POC. |\n| [`nosecrets-core`](https://docs.rs/nosecrets-core/0.3.7/nosecrets_core/) | Maybe, but file-oriented | MIT, core engine, entropy module, uses rules/filter/report crates. Looks built around scanning files and returning masked previews, less natural for “scan this transcript JSON value.” |\n| [`secretscan`](https://docs.rs/secretscan/latest/secretscan/) | Maybe, but repo/file-oriented | MIT and has entropy helpers plus scanner APIs, but the public API is more directory scanner than string redactor. Could work, but not as clean. |\n| [`gitleaks`](https://github.com/gitleaks/gitleaks) | Great tool, wrong shape | Mature, supports `stdin`, JSON/SARIF, entropy rules, and `--redact`, but it is Go/CLI. Shelling out feels too much for this POC. |\n| [`Kingfisher`](https://github.com/mongodb/kingfisher) / [`Leaktor`](https://github.com/reschjonas/leaktor) | Powerful, too much | Both are Rust secret scanners with broad coverage and validation workflows. Better as external tools than embedded transcript redaction for this feature. |\n| [`threatdeflect-core`](https://docs.rs/crate/threatdeflect-core/0.1.3) / [`key-watch`](https://crates.io/crates/key-watch) | Skip | GPL-licensed, so I’d avoid pulling them into GitButler. |\n| [`ripsecrets`](https://docs.rs/crate/ripsecrets/0.1.11) | Skip for embed | Nice local-only philosophy, but exposed as a CLI and docs coverage is effectively absent. |\n\nMy pragmatic recommendation: use `hazler-secrets` for the POC, but keep it deliberately blunt. When `--include-transcript` is on, recursively scan string values in the parsed `source_record`; if a string has any pattern or entropy finding, replace the whole string with something like `\"[REDACTED:secret]\"`. Don’t scan metadata-only captures, don’t shell out, don’t add validation, don’t try to invent our own entropy logic.\n\nImportant detail: dedupe/source hashes should still use the original raw JSONL record. The stored envelope can include `source_record_redacted: true` or `redactions_count` so the hash mismatch is understandable rather than spooky.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:31:17.813Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}